<section id="sexagenary">
  <h2>The Sexagenary Cycle (<span class="chinese-char">六十甲子</span>)</h2>
  <p>The <strong>sexagenary cycle</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">六十甲子</span>, Li&ugrave;sh&iacute; Ji&abreve;z&ibreve;) is the backbone of the Chinese calendar&rsquo;s counting system. It combines two ordered sets:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>10 Heavenly Stems</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">天干</span>, Ti&amacr;ng&amacr;n): <span class="chinese-char">甲</span> Ji&abreve;, <span class="chinese-char">乙</span> Y&ibreve;, <span class="chinese-char">丙</span> B&ibreve;ng, <span class="chinese-char">丁</span> D&imacr;ng, <span class="chinese-char">戊</span> W&ugrave;, <span class="chinese-char">己</span> J&ibreve;, <span class="chinese-char">庚</span> G&emacr;ng, <span class="chinese-char">辛</span> X&imacr;n, <span class="chinese-char">壬</span> R&eacute;n, <span class="chinese-char">癸</span> Gu&ibreve;</li>
    <li><strong>12 Earthly Branches</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">地支</span>, D&igrave;zh&imacr;): <span class="chinese-char">子</span> Z&ibreve;, <span class="chinese-char">丑</span> Ch&oacute;u, <span class="chinese-char">寅</span> Y&iacute;n, <span class="chinese-char">卯</span> M&abreve;o, <span class="chinese-char">辰</span> Ch&eacute;n, <span class="chinese-char">巳</span> S&igrave;, <span class="chinese-char">午</span> W&ubreve;, <span class="chinese-char">未</span> W&egrave;i, <span class="chinese-char">申</span> Sh&emacr;n, <span class="chinese-char">酉</span> Y&oacute;u, <span class="chinese-char">戌</span> X&umacr;, <span class="chinese-char">亥</span> H&agrave;i</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The stems and branches are paired sequentially &mdash; the first stem with the first branch, the second stem with the second branch, and so on. Because yang stems (odd-numbered: 1st, 3rd, 5th, 7th, 9th) pair only with yang branches (odd-numbered: 1st, 3rd, 5th, 7th, 9th, 11th), and yin stems with yin branches, the system produces exactly <strong>60 unique combinations</strong> before cycling back to the beginning. This 60-unit cycle is used to count <strong>years, months, days, and double-hours</strong>.</p>

  <p><strong>Oracle bone inscriptions</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">甲骨文</span>) from the Shang dynasty (c. 1600&ndash;1046 BCE) already use the full sexagenary cycle for day-counting, making it one of the <strong>oldest continuous timekeeping systems</strong> in human history &mdash; over 3,000 years of unbroken daily use. The year cycle was standardised later but follows the same logic.</p>

  <p>The sexagenary cycle is the foundation of <a href="/bazi/">BaZi (Four Pillars of Destiny)</a> astrology, where each pillar (year, month, day, hour) is expressed as a Stem-Branch pair. It also determines the <a href="/zodiac/">zodiac animal</a> (via the Earthly Branch) and the <a href="/wuxing/">element</a> (via the Heavenly Stem) of each year.</p>

