<section id="solar-terms">
  <h2>The 24 Solar Terms (<span class="chinese-char">二十四節氣</span>)</h2>
  <p>The <strong>24 solar terms</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">二十四節氣</span>, &Egrave;rsh&iacute;s&igrave; Ji&eacute;q&igrave;) are the Chinese calendar&rsquo;s solar backbone. They divide the <strong>tropical year</strong> into 24 segments of approximately 15 days each, based on the Sun&rsquo;s position along the ecliptic (every 15&deg; of ecliptic longitude). Unlike the lunar months, solar terms are fixed to the solar year and fall on nearly the same Gregorian dates each year.</p>

  <p>The solar terms were codified during the <a href="/dynasties/">Han dynasty</a> and inscribed into <strong>UNESCO&rsquo;s Representative List of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity</strong> in 2016, recognising their profound cultural and scientific significance. They govern agriculture, festival timing, and &mdash; critically for <a href="/bazi/">BaZi</a> practitioners &mdash; they define the boundaries of BaZi months. The term <strong>Lichun</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">立春</span>, Start of Spring) marks the beginning of the BaZi year.</p>

